<section id="vitamin-d3">
    <h2>Vitamin D3: The Foundation</h2>

    <div class="supplement-card">
        <h3>Vitamin D3 (Cholecalciferol)</h3>
        <p><strong>Dose:</strong> 5,000 IU daily (125 mcg)</p>
        <p><strong>With food:</strong> Fat-soluble, take with meals</p>

        <h4>Why You're Deficient:</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Indoor lifestyle</li>
            <li>Sunscreen blocks production</li>
            <li>Darker skin = less production</li>
            <li>Age reduces synthesis</li>
            <li>Obesity sequesters D3</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Cardiovascular Benefits:</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Improves calcium absorption from food</li>
            <li>Reduces inflammation</li>
            <li>Lowers blood pressure</li>
            <li>Improves insulin sensitivity</li>
            <li>Supports immune function</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Testing:</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Test 25-hydroxyvitamin D</li>
            <li>Optimal: 50-80 ng/mL</li>
            <li>Below 30 = deficient</li>
            <li>Retest every 3-6 months initially</li>
        </ul>
    </div>
</section>

<section id="vitamin-k2">
    <h2>Vitamin K2: The Missing Link</h2>

    <div class="supplement-card">
        <h3>Vitamin K2 (MK-7 form)</h3>
        <p><strong>Dose:</strong> 200 mcg daily</p>
        <p><strong>Timing:</strong> With D3 and fat</p>

        <h4>The Arterial Protection Factor:</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Activates osteocalcin (pulls calcium INTO bones)</li>
            <li>Activates MGP (pulls calcium OUT of arteries)</li>
            <li>Prevents arterial calcification</li>
            <li>May reverse existing calcification</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Why You Don't Get Enough:</h4>
        <ul>
            <li>Found in fermented foods (we don't eat)</li>
            <li>Grass-fed animal products (not grain-fed)</li>
            <li>Destroyed by antibiotics</li>
            <li>Not in plant foods</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="warning-box">
            <strong>Blood Thinner Alert:</strong>
            Warfarin (Coumadin) blocks K1 AND K2. This accelerates arterial calcification. Discuss alternatives with your doctor.
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

